82
00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:19,090
But the way that your, your instinct might
be to compare those

83
00:04:19,090 --> 00:04:24,410
groups by just comparing the means, the
345.5 versus the 18.5 pound weight loss.

84
00:04:24,410 --> 00:04:25,340
If you did that,

85
00:04:25,340 --> 00:04:27,760
you would compare those two means with a
test that we called a T-Test.

86
00:04:27,760 --> 00:04:28,880
Some of you may of heard of.

87
00:04:28,880 --> 00:04:31,050
If you do that you will find.

88
00:04:31,050 --> 00:04:33,670
That there is no significant difference
between the groups.

89
00:04:33,670 --> 00:04:36,650
So what you need to compare in this case
is not the means but

90
00:04:36,650 --> 00:04:39,300
you need to compare the medians.

91
00:04:39,300 --> 00:04:44,100
You need to compare the data using a
ranked data procedure something called

92
00:04:44,100 --> 00:04:45,650
a non-parametric test.

93
00:04:45,650 --> 00:04:48,930
And don't worry to much about this
terminology right now we're going to

94
00:04:48,930 --> 00:04:52,800
talk a lot about non-parametric tests in a
future week.

95
00:04:52,800 --> 00:04:54,700
But some of you may have heard that term
before.

96
00:04:54,700 --> 00:04:55,990
So this is an example,

97
00:04:55,990 --> 00:04:58,320
what I'm going to show you now is an
example of a non-parametric test.

98
00:04:58,320 --> 00:05:00,310
That just means that we're going to be
ranking the,

99
00:05:00,310 --> 00:05:05,680
the data and running tests on the ranks of
the data rather than the raw values.

100
00:05:05,680 --> 00:05:09,970
And it's, the tests that I'm actually
going to run now I'm going to tell you

101
00:05:09,970 --> 00:05:12,770
the name of it only because it has a very
informative name.

102
00:05:12,770 --> 00:05:16,090
It's something called the Wilcoxon
rank-sum test and don't worry about

103
00:05:17,090 --> 00:05:21,160
the details of that yet, we'll return to
that test in another couple of weeks but

104
00:05:21,160 --> 00:05:25,520
it's very easy to figure out what the test
does because it is a rank-sum test.

105
00:05:25,520 --> 00:05:27,360
So literally we're going to rank the data
and

106
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:30,650
then we're going to sum the data and that
part is easy to understand without knowing

107
00:05:30,650 --> 00:05:33,410
anything about non-parametric tests so
we're going to do that.

108
00:05:33,410 --> 00:05:34,800
We can do that right now.

109
00:05:34,800 --> 00:05:35,710
So let's rank the data.

110
00:05:35,710 --> 00:05:37,810
So what do I mean by ranking the data?

111
00:05:37,810 --> 00:05:41,720
So what we're going to do, is we're
going to order the data from the lowest

112
00:05:41,720 --> 00:05:45,610
weight loss, the, the worst weight loss to
the highest, the best weight loss.

113
00:05:45,610 --> 00:05:46,770
And for the moment,

114
00:05:46,770 --> 00:05:49,925
we're going to rank the data ignoring
which group people are in.

115
00:05:49,925 --> 00:05:52,100
So, there are 20 people here.

116
00:05:52,100 --> 00:05:54,250
The person who lost the least weight,

117
00:05:54,250 --> 00:05:56,240
which was the person who gained four
pounds.

118
00:05:56,240 --> 00:05:57,890
They're going to get a rank of one.

119
00:05:57,890 --> 00:06:00,530
The person who lost the most weight, which
was the person who was

120
00:06:00,530 --> 00:06:04,280
just did really well and lost 300 pounds,
they're going to get a rank of 20.

121
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:06,240
And we're going to rank everybody in
between.

122
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:09,040
And again, for the moment we're ignorning
diet.

123
00:06:09,040 --> 00:06:13,750
So, you can see that most of the low ranks
go to diet one.

124
00:06:13,750 --> 00:06:16,370
The, the six lowest ranks go to diet one.

125
00:06:16,370 --> 00:06:20,960
The sixth lowest person lost only five
pounds, and then we jump to diet two.

126
00:06:20,960 --> 00:06:24,569
The eight pound weight loss in diet two
was the seventh lowest.

127
00:06:24,569 --> 00:06:27,740
And then the negative ten, the ten pound
weight loss was the eighth, and

128
00:06:27,740 --> 00:06:31,110
then we jump back to diet one to get the
ninth rank, and so on.

129
00:06:31,110 --> 00:06:34,620
So you can see, that now we're treating
everything rather than using

130
00:06:34,620 --> 00:06:39,820
the underlying values like the negative
300, which is so highly influential.

131
00:06:39,820 --> 00:06:42,180
We're giving everybody a rate, and

132
00:06:42,180 --> 00:06:46,580
the rate values you can see everybody is
only one unit apart.

133
00:06:46,580 --> 00:06:49,520
So that's going to have less influence on
the statistics.

134
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:53,680
Notice, however though, that we did not
take that 300 pound weight loss and

135
00:06:53,680 --> 00:06:56,760
throw it out, that would be a mistake,
because there really is

136
00:06:56,760 --> 00:07:01,700
somebody who did have a fabulous success
on diet one for whatever reason.

137
00:07:01,700 --> 00:07:05,680
That person gets counted, they get the
best rate, they get the 20, but

138
00:07:05,680 --> 00:07:09,560
that, that the 20 has much less influence
on the statistics than that negative 300,

139
00:07:09,560 --> 00:07:10,400
that's the idea.

140
00:07:10,400 --> 00:07:13,790
So we ranked everybody from 1 to 20,
ignoring which group you're in.

141
00:07:13,790 --> 00:07:16,810
And then, we sum up the ranks within each
of those groups,

142
00:07:16,810 --> 00:07:19,050
we just add them up, literally sum them
up.

143
00:07:19,050 --> 00:07:21,860
So, we take the ranks from diet one and we
add them up,

144
00:07:21,860 --> 00:07:26,370
we come up with a sum of the ranks of 73,
do the same thing with diet two,

145
00:07:26,370 --> 00:07:28,496
we come up with a sum of the ranks of 137.

146
00:07:28,496 --> 00:07:34,160
Notice that 137 is much bigger than 73,.

147
00:07:34,160 --> 00:07:37,970
Where we need the official, the formal
Wilcoxon sum-rank test is to

148
00:07:37,970 --> 00:07:41,790
actually say whether or not that 137
versus that 73.

149
00:07:41,790 --> 00:07:44,090
Whether that's a different set, could have
arisen by chance or

150
00:07:44,090 --> 00:07:47,280
does that represent likely a real
difference between those diets.

151
00:07:47,280 --> 00:07:50,510
And so when we actually apply the formal
Wilcoxon sum-rank test,

152
00:07:50,510 --> 00:07:52,970
something we're going to learn in a few
weeks, to say whether or

153
00:07:52,970 --> 00:07:58,790
not 137 is really different than 73, in
fact, we get a significant p-value here.

154
00:07:58,790 --> 00:08:02,620
So, in fact, when you apply the correct
statistical test here,

155
00:08:02,620 --> 00:08:07,010
you find out that diet two is
significantly better than diet one.

156
00:08:07,010 --> 00:08:09,760
Exactly the opposite of what you might
have concluded if you had

157
00:08:09,760 --> 00:08:10,870
just looked at the means.
